profiles.title: Cancer Disease Status Profile
profiles.description: A clinician's qualitative judgment on the current trend of the cancer, e.g., whether it is stable, worsening (progressing), or improving (responding). The judgment may be based a single type or multiple kinds of evidence, such as imaging data, assessment of symptoms, tumor markers, laboratory data, etc.

profiles.title: Cancer Patient Profile
profiles.description: A patient who has been diagnosed with or is receiving medical treatment for a malignant growth or tumor. The is the most essential profile in mCODE, since it is referenced by many other profiles. The only difference between the mCODE Patient profile and the [US Core Patient Profile](http://hl7.org/fhir/us/core/StructureDefinition-us-core-patient.html) is that Patient.deceased is a [must-support](https://www.hl7.org/fhir/profiling.html#mustsupport) element in mCODE.

profiles.title: Cancer Stage Group Profile
profiles.description: The extent of the cancer in the body, according to a given cancer staging classification system, based on evidence such as physical examination, imaging, and/or biopsy or based on pathologic analysis of a specimen.

profiles.title: Cancer-Related Medication Administration Profile
profiles.description: An episode of medication administration for a patient whose condition is related to a primary or secondary cancer condition. In the context of chemotherapy drugs, the medication administration in most cases is performed and documented by the provider.

profiles.title: Cancer-Related Medication Request Profile
profiles.description: A record of a medication prescription or consumption associated with cancer treatment. The medication may reported by the prescriber, prescribing organization, or patient. It does not have to be directly observed.

profiles.title: Cancer-Related Surgical Procedure Profile
profiles.description: A surgical action addressing a cancer condition. The scope of this profile has been narrowed to cancer-related procedures by constraining the reasonReference and reasonCode to cancer conditions, one of which is required.

profiles.title: Comorbidities Elixhauser Profile
profiles.description: Comorbid condition checklist and optional risk score, using Elixhauser comorbidity categories as defined by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project (H-CUP).

profiles.title: Comorbidities Parent Abstract Profile
profiles.description: General structure for capturing comorbid conditions with respect to a primary ('index') condition. The specific set of comorbidities of interest in a given context are defined by slicing the components array. The same general approach can be applied to any comorbidity category checklist.

profiles.title: ECOG Performance Status Profile
profiles.description: The Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG) Performance Status represents the patient's functional status and is used to determine their ability to tolerate therapies in serious illness, specifically for chemotherapy. (Definition from: [LOINC](https://loinc.org/89262-0/))

profiles.title: Genomic Region Studied Profile
profiles.description: A subset of genes or genomic regions of interest in a targeted resequencing study.

profiles.title: Genomic Specimen Profile
profiles.description: A small sample of blood, hair, skin, amniotic fluid (the fluid that surrounds a fetus during pregnancy), or other tissue which is excised from a subject for the purposes of genomics testing or analysis.

profiles.title: Genomic Variant Profile
profiles.description: An alteration in the most common DNA nucleotide sequence. The term variant can be used to describe an alteration that may be benign, pathogenic, or of unknown significance. The term variant is increasingly being used in place of the term mutation. Variants can be computed relative to reference sequence assembly from which it was identified.

profiles.title: Genomics Report Profile
profiles.description: Genomic analysis summary report. The report may include one or more tests, with two distinct test types. The first type is a targeted mutation test, where a specific mutation on a specific gene is tested for. The result is either positive or negative for that mutation. The second type is a more general test for variants. This type of test returns the identity of variants found in a certain region of the genome.

profiles.title: Karnofsky Performance Status Profile
profiles.description: The Karnofsky Performance Status (KPS) is a tool used to measure a patient's functional status. It can be used to compare the effectiveness of different therapies and to help assess the prognosis of certain patients, such as those with certain cancers. The KPS score ranges from 0 to 100 in intervals of 10. Higher scores are associated with better functional status, with 100 representing no symptoms or evidence of disease, and 0 representing death.

profiles.title: Primary Cancer Condition Profile
profiles.description: Records the the primary cancer condition, the original or first tumor in the body (Definition from: [NCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms](https://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/primary-tumor)). Cancers that are not clearly secondary (i.e., of uncertain origin or behavior) should be documented as primary.

profiles.title: Radiotherapy Course Summary Profile
profiles.description: A summary of a course of radiotherapy delivered to a patient. It records the treatment intent, termination reason, modalities, techniques, number of sessions, and doses delivered to one or more body volumes. Whether the course has been fully delivered or stopped is indicated in the status element.

profiles.title: Radiotherapy Volume Profile
profiles.description: A volume of the body used in radiotherapy planning or treatment delivery.

profiles.title: Secondary Cancer Condition Profile
profiles.description: Records the history of secondary neoplasms, including location(s) and the date of onset of metastases. A secondary cancer results from the spread (metastasization) of cancer from its original site (Definition from: NCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms).

profiles.title: TNM Distant Metastases Category Profile
profiles.description: Category describing the extent of a tumor metastasis in remote anatomical locations, based on evidence such as physical examination, imaging, and/or biopsy.

profiles.title: TNM Primary Tumor Category Profile
profiles.description: Category of the primary tumor, based on its size and extent, based on evidence such as physical examination, imaging, and/or biopsy.

profiles.title: TNM Regional Nodes Category Profile
profiles.description: Category of the presence or absence of metastases in regional lymph nodes, based on evidence such as physical examination, imaging, and/or biopsy.

profiles.title: Tumor Marker Test Profile
profiles.description: The result of a tumor marker test. Tumor marker tests are generally used to guide cancer treatment decisions and monitor treatment, as well as to predict the chance of recovery and cancer recurrence.

profiles.title: Tumor Profile
profiles.description: Identifies a tumor that has not been removed from the body. Whenever possible, a single resource conforming to this profile will be used to track a tumor over time (as opposed to creating new Tumor-conforming BodyStructure resources each time that tumor is measured). Use TumorSpecimen to represent the tumor after removal from the body.

profiles.title: Tumor Size Profile
profiles.description: Records the dimensions of a tumor

profiles.title: Tumor Specimen Profile
profiles.description: Represents a tumor after it has been removed from the body. If there is a Tumor resource representing the tumor before it was removed from the body, use `identifier` to associate this TumorSpecimen with that Tumor resource.

profiles.title: mCODE Patient Bundle Profile
profiles.description: A collection of data for an mCODE cancer patient.

profiles.title: mCODE Patient Group Profile
profiles.description: A group of patients included in the scope of mCODE, whose cancer-related resources conform to mCODE profiles.

profileElements.Definition: Categorization of the kind of evidence contributing to a clinical judgment on cancer disease progression.
The status of the result value.

The patient, or group of patients, location, or device this observation is about and into whose record the observation is placed. If the actual focus of the observation is different from the subject (or a sample of, part, or region of the subject), the `focus` element or the `code` itself specifies the actual focus of the observation.

The actual focus of an observation when it is not the patient of record representing something or someone associated with the patient such as a spouse, parent, fetus, or donor. For example, fetus observations in a mother's record.  The focus of an observation could also be an existing condition,  an intervention, the subject's diet,  another observation of the subject,  or a body structure such as tumor or implanted device.   An example use case would be using the Observation resource to capture whether the mother is trained to change her child's tracheostomy tube. In this example, the child is the patient of record and the mother is the focus.

The time or time-period the observed value is asserted as being true. For biological subjects - e.g. human patients - this is usually called the "physiologically relevant time". This is usually either the time of the procedure or of specimen collection, but very often the source of the date/time is not known, only the date/time itself.
The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.
Provides a reason why the expected value in the element Observation.value[x] is missing.
An identifier for this patient.
Establishes the namespace for the value - that is, a URL that describes a set values that are unique.
The portion of the identifier typically relevant to the user and which is unique within the context of the system.
A name associated with the individual.
The part of a name that links to the genealogy. In some cultures (e.g. Eritrea) the family name of a son is the first name of his father.
Given name.
Telecommunications form for contact point - what communications system is required to make use of the contact.
The actual contact point details, in a form that is meaningful to the designated communication system (i.e. phone number or email address).
Identifies the purpose for the contact point.
Administrative Gender - the gender that the patient is considered to have for administration and record keeping purposes.
The date of birth for the individual.
Indicates if the individual is deceased or not.
An address for the individual.
This component contains the house number, apartment number, street name, street direction,  P.O. Box number, delivery hints, and similar address information.
The name of the city, town, suburb, village or other community or delivery center.
Sub-unit of a country with limited sovereignty in a federally organized country. A code may be used if codes are in common use (e.g. US 2 letter state codes).
A postal code designating a region defined by the postal service.
Time period when address was/is in use.

The ISO-639-1 alpha 2 code in lower case for the language, optionally followed by a hyphen and the ISO-3166-1 alpha 2 code for the region in upper case; e.g. "en" for English, or "en-US" for American English versus "en-EN" for England English.
The purpose of a procedure.
A code explaining the unplanned or premature termination, or normal completion, of a plan of treatment, course of medication, or research study.

Will generally be set to show that the administration has been completed.  For some long running administrations such as infusions, it is possible for an administration to be started but not completed or it may be paused while some other process is under way.

Identifies the medication that was administered. This is either a link to a resource representing the details of the medication or a simple attribute carrying a code that identifies the medication from a known list of medications.
The person or animal or group receiving the medication.

A specific date/time or interval of time during which the administration took place (or did not take place, when the 'notGiven' attribute is true). For many administrations, such as swallowing a tablet the use of dateTime is more appropriate.
A code indicating why the medication was given.
Condition or observation that supports why the medication was administered.
The purpose of a procedure.
A code explaining the unplanned or premature termination, or normal completion, of a plan of treatment, course of medication, or research study.
A code specifying the current state of the order.  Generally, this will be active or completed state.
Whether the request is a proposal, plan, or an original order.
Indicates the type of medication request (for example, where the medication is expected to be consumed or administered (i.e. inpatient or outpatient)).
Indicates if this record was captured as a secondary 'reported' record rather than as an original primary source-of-truth record.  It may also indicate the source of the report.
profileElements.Data Type: boolean or Reference: USCorePractitionerProfile, USCoreOrganizationProfile, USCorePatientProfile, USCorePractitionerRoleProfile, or RelatedPerson

profileElements.Definition: Identifies the medication being requested. This is a link to a resource that represents the medication which may be the details of the medication or simply an attribute carrying a code that identifies the medication from a known list of medications.
A link to a resource representing the person or set of individuals to whom the medication will be given.
The Encounter during which this [x] was created or to which the creation of this record is tightly associated.
The date (and perhaps time) when the prescription was initially written or authored on.
The individual, organization, or device that initiated the request and has responsibility for its activation.
The reason or the indication for ordering or not ordering the medication.
Condition or observation that supports why the medication was ordered.
Indicates how the medication is to be used by the patient.
Free text dosage instructions e.g. SIG.
profileElements.Required?: Required if known (conditional on Dosage Instruction)

profileElements.Definition: The purpose of a procedure.
A code specifying the state of the procedure. Generally, this will be the in-progress or completed state.
The specific procedure that is performed. Use text if the exact nature of the procedure cannot be coded (e.g. "Laparoscopic Appendectomy").
The person, animal or group on which the procedure was performed.

Estimated or actual date, date-time, period, or age when the procedure was performed.  Allows a period to support complex procedures that span more than one date, and also allows for the length of the procedure to be captured.
profileElements.Data Type: dateTime, Period, string, Age, or Range

profileElements.Definition: The coded reason why the procedure was performed. This may be a coded entity of some type, or may simply be present as text.
The justification of why the procedure was performed.
Detailed and structured anatomical location information. Multiple locations are allowed - e.g. multiple punch biopsies of a lesion.
General location qualifier (excluding laterality) for this bodySite

The patient, or group of patients, location, or device this observation is about and into whose record the observation is placed. If the actual focus of the observation is different from the subject (or a sample of, part, or region of the subject), the `focus` element or the `code` itself specifies the actual focus of the observation.

The actual focus of an observation when it is not the patient of record representing something or someone associated with the patient such as a spouse, parent, fetus, or donor. For example, fetus observations in a mother's record.  The focus of an observation could also be an existing condition,  an intervention, the subject's diet,  another observation of the subject,  or a body structure such as tumor or implanted device.   An example use case would be using the Observation resource to capture whether the mother is trained to change her child's tracheostomy tube. In this example, the child is the patient of record and the mother is the focus.

If the actual focus of the observation is different from the subject (or a sample of, part, or region of the subject), the `focus` element or the `code` itself specifies the actual focus of the observation.

The actual focus of an observation when it is not the patient of record representing something or someone associated with the patient such as a spouse, parent, fetus, or donor. For example, fetus observations in a mother's record.  The focus of an observation could also be an existing condition,  an intervention, the subject's diet,  another observation of the subject,  or a body structure such as tumor or implanted device.   An example use case would be using the Observation resource to capture whether the mother is trained to change her child's tracheostomy tube. valueSets.title: Cancer Body Location Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the location(s) of primary or secondary cancer. The value set includes all codes from the SNOMED CT body structure hierarchy (codes descending from 123037004 'Body Structure'). The cancer body location may also be expressed using ICD-O-3 topography codes, however, those codes are not included here due to intellectual property restrictions. These topography terms have four-character codes that run from C00.0 to C80.9 [ref](https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/96612/9789241548496_eng.pdf). Only SNOMED CT and ICD-O-3 are considered conformant.

valueSets.title: Cancer Disease Status Evidence Type Value Set
valueSets.description: The type of evidence backing up the clinical determination of cancer progression.

valueSets.title: Cancer Disorder Value Set
valueSets.description: A broad cancer-related value set containing both primary and secondary tumor types, with codes from ICD-10 and SNOMED CT, including both diagnosis and histology/morphology/behavior codes. ICD-O-3 morphology codes may also be used and are considered conformant to the specification. For SNOMED, the value set includes all codes descending from 363346000 'Malignant neoplastic disease (disorder)' and 108369006 'Neoplasm (morphologic abnormality)'.

valueSets.title: Cancer-Related Surgical Procedure Value Set
valueSets.description: Includes surgical procedure codes from SNOMED CT, ICD-10-PCS and CPT. The value set may be a superset of cancer surgery codes, but narrowing the set further risks eliminating potentially useful and relevant codes.

valueSets.title: Cancer Stage Group Value Set
valueSets.description: This value set is intended to contain allowable values for Stage Group, according to TNM staging rules. AJCC codes (preferably, version 8 for current cancers) SHOULD be used.

valueSets.title: Cancer Staging System Value Set
valueSets.description: System used for staging.

valueSets.title: Carcinoma In-Situ Disorder Value Set
valueSets.description: Types of carcinoma in-situ, coded in SNOMED CT or ICD-10-CM.

valueSets.title: ClinVar Value Set
valueSets.description: Value set of human genomic variants, drawn from [ClinVar](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/clinvar/). The codes in this value set refer to the ClinVar Variation ID, or the identifier for the variant or set of variants that were interpreted. [Source: NCBI ClinVar Data Dictionary](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/projects/clinvar/ClinVarDataDictionary.pdf)

valueSets.title: Condition Status Trend Value Set
valueSets.description: How patient's given disease, condition, or ability is trending.

valueSets.title: Cytologic Evidence of Malignancy Value Set
valueSets.description: Types of cytological evience of malignancy, coded in SNOMED CT or ICD-10-CM.

valueSets.title: DNA Change Type Value Set
valueSets.description: DNA Change Type of a variant

valueSets.title: Genomic Molecular Consequence Value Set
valueSets.description: Changes in a structural features of a sequence due to the observed variant.

valueSets.title: Genomic Specimen Type Value Set
valueSets.description: The type of specimen analyzed in a genomic test. The values include the subset of codes in the HL7 Specimen Type code system (https://terminology.hl7.org/2.1.0/CodeSystem-v2-0487.html) representing body sites and body fluids likely to be used in genomic testing.  The most specific term available should be used.

valueSets.title: HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee Gene Names Value Set
valueSets.description: HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee Gene Names Value Set

valueSets.title: Human Genome Variation Society Sequence Variant Nomenclature Value Set
valueSets.description: HGVS nomenclature is used to report and exchange information regarding variants found in DNA, RNA, and protein sequences.

valueSets.title: Histology Morphology Behavior Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes representing the structure, arrangement, and behavioral characteristics of malignant neoplasms, and cancer cells. Inclusion criteria: in situ neoplasms and malignant neoplasms. Exclusion criteria: benign neoplasms and neoplasms of unspecified behavior. Note: ICD-O-3 morphology codes are referenced in the logical definition but not expanded in the value set for intellectual property reasons. For primary cancers, the ICD-O-3 behavior suffix should be /1, /2, or /3. For secondary cancers, the ICD-O-3 behavior suffix should be /6.

valueSets.title: Specific Diagnosis of Cancer Value Set
valueSets.description: Types of hypereosinophilic syndrome, coded in SNOMED CT or ICD-10-CM.

valueSets.title: Laterality Qualifier Value Set
valueSets.description: Qualifiers to specify laterality.

valueSets.title: Melanoma In-Situ Disorder Value Set
valueSets.description: Types of melanoma in-situ, coded in SNOMED CT or ICD-10-CM.

valueSets.title: Staging Type Value Set (for Distant Metastases Category)
valueSets.description: Identifying codes based on the timing of classification for distant metastases (M) staging observations.

valueSets.title: Staging Type for Primary Tumor Category Value Set
valueSets.description: Identifying codes based on the timing of classification for primary tumor (T) staging observations.

valueSets.title: Staging Type for Regional Node Category Value Set
valueSets.description: Identifying codes based on the timing of classification for regional node (N) staging observations.

valueSets.title: Staging Type for Stage Group Value Set
valueSets.description: Identifying codes based on the timing of classification for stage group observations.

valueSets.title: Present Absent Value Set
valueSets.description: Value set used in association with phenomena that can be observed as being present or absent, such as a finding, organism, or physical object.

valueSets.title: Primary Cancer Disorder Value Set
valueSets.description: Types of primary malignant neoplastic disease, coded in SNOMED CT or ICD-10-CM.

valueSets.title: Primary Malignant Neoplasm Disorder Value Set
valueSets.description: Types of primary malignant neoplasms, coded in SNOMED CT or ICD-10-CM.

valueSets.title: Procedure Intent Value Set
valueSets.description: The purpose of a procedure.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Modality Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the modalities of external beam and brachytherapy radiation procedures, for use with radiotherapy summaries.  This value set is the union of the teleradiotherapy and brachytherapy modality value sets.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the techniques of external beam and brachytherapy radiation procedures, for use with radiotherapy summaries. This is the union of the EBRT and brachytherapy technique value sets.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Treatment Location Qualifier Value Set
valueSets.description: Various modifiers that can be applied to body locations where radiotherapy treatments can be directed.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Treatment Location Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the body locations where radiotherapy treatments can be directed. Based on TG263.

valueSets.title: Radiotherapy Volume Type Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the types of body volumes used in radiotherapy planning and treatment. The value set includes the most common codes from DICOM CID 9534 Radiotherapy Targets (UID 1.2.840.10008.6.1.1244) and adds a code for Organs at Risk (OAR).

valueSets.title: Secondary Cancer Disorder Value Set
valueSets.description: Types of secondary malignant neoplastic disease, coded in SNOMED CT or ICD-10-CM.

valueSets.title: Carbon Ion Beam Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Allowed techniques for carbon ion beam modality

valueSets.title: Electron Beam Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Allowed techniques for electron beam modality

valueSets.title: Teleradiotherapy Modality Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the modalities of teleradiotherapy (external beam) procedures.

valueSets.title: Neutron Beam Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Allowed techniques for neutron beam modality

valueSets.title: Photon Beam Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Allowed techniques for photon beam modality

valueSets.title: Proton Beam Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Allowed techniques for proton beam modality

valueSets.title: Teleradiotherapy Technique Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes describing the techniques of teleradiotherapy (external beam) procedures.

valueSets.title: TNM Distant Metastases Category Value Set
valueSets.description: This value set is intended to contain allowable values for the M category, according to TNM staging rules. AJCC codes (preferably, version 8 for current cancers) SHOULD be used.

valueSets.title: TNM Primary Tumor Category Value Set
valueSets.description: This value set is intended to contain allowable values for the T category, according to TNM staging rules. AJCC codes (preferably, version 8 for current cancers) SHOULD be used.

valueSets.title: TNM Regional Nodes Category Value Set
valueSets.description: This value set is intended to contain allowable values for the N category, according to TNM staging rules. AJCC codes (preferably, version 8 for current cancers) SHOULD be used.

valueSets.title: Treatment Termination Reason Value Set
valueSets.description: Values used to describe the reasons for stopping a treatment or episode of care. Includes code for 'treatment completed' as well as codes for unplanned (early) stoppage. Applies to medications and other treatments that take place over a period of time, such as radiation treatments.

valueSets.title: Tumor Marker Test Value Set
valueSets.description: Codes representing tests for tumor markers. This value set of LOINC codes is not comprehensive and can be extended. Other vocabularies can be used only if the test of interest is not covered by LOINC. Tumor marker tests differ from genetic tests in that they measure levels of protein or other substances produced downstream from RNA protein synthesis.

valueSets.title: Tumor Size Method Value Set
valueSets.description: Code for methods of measuring tumor size, including physical examination, pathology, and imaging.

valueSets.title: Tumor Size Units Value Set
valueSets.description: Acceptable units for measuring tumor size

extensions.description: Qualifier to refine an body location. These include qualifiers for relative location, directionality, number, and plane, and exclude qualifiers for laterality.

extensions.title: Cancer Disease Status Evidence Type Extension
extensions.description: Categorization of the kind of evidence contributing to a clinical judgment on cancer disease progression.

extensions.title: Comorbid Condition Code Extension
extensions.description: An extension for representing a specific condition code corresponding to the comorbid condition category.

extensions.title: Comorbid Condition Reference Extension
extensions.description: An extension for representing a reference to a condition resource corresponding to the comorbid condition category.

extensions.title: Histology-Morphology-Behavior Extension
extensions.description: An extension describing the morphologic and behavioral characteristics of the cancer.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Dose Delivered To Volume Extension
extensions.description: Dose delivered to a given radiotherapy volume.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Modality And Technique Extension
extensions.description: Extension capturing modality and technique of a given radiotherapy procedure.  The allowed combinations of modality and technique are constrained by invariants, one per modality.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Modality Extension
extensions.description: Extension capturing a modality of external beam or brachytherapy radiation procedures.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Number of Sessions Extension
extensions.description: The number of sessions in a course of radiotherapy.

extensions.title: Radiotherapy Technique Extension
extensions.description: Extension capturing a technique of external beam or brachytherapy radiation procedures.

extensions.title: Related Condition Extension
extensions.description: The resource has an unspecified relationship with a Condition.

extensions.title: Treatment Termination Reason Extension
extensions.description: A code explaining the unplanned or premature termination, or normal completion, of a plan of treatment, course of medication, or research study.

codeSystems.title: Requested LOINC Codes Code System
codeSystems.description: Codes requested from LOINC, but not yet approved or assigned. Codes related to comorbidities use the categories originally defined by Elixhauser, and updated by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project (H-CUP) [Elixhauser Comorbidity Software Refined for ICD-10-CM v2021.1](https://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/toolssoftware/comorbidityicd10/comorbidity_icd10.jsp). Each comorbidity category is associated with a specific ICD-10-CM value set. For example, the category #CHF (congestive heart failure) refers to the patient having a diagnosis within the [Elixhauser Comorbid Condition Value Set for Congestive Heart Failure](http://hl7.org/fhir/us/mcode/ValueSet/elixhauser-congestive-heart-failure-vs).

codeSystems.title: Requested SNOMED Codes Code System
codeSystems.description: Codes requested from SNOMED by mCODE, to be issued at a later date. Where numeric codes are given, these correspond to the expected SNOMED-CT codes. Terms beginning with 'USCRS-' (for United States Content Request Service) represent request identifiers with no SNOMED code yet approved or assigned.
